{{About|the book by Rudy Rucker||Fourth dimension (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox book | name = The Fourth Dimension | image = The Fourth Dimension (Rudy Rucker book - cover art).jpg | caption = First edition cover | author = [[Rudy Rucker]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Mathematics]] | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]] | pub_date = September 1, 1984 | media_type = Print | pages = 228 | isbn = 978-0395344200 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Fourth Dimension''''' is a [[non-fiction]] work written by [[Rudy Rucker]], the [[Silicon Valley]] professor of mathematics and computer science, and was published in 1984 by Houghton Mifflin. The book is subtitled as a guided tour of the higher universes. The foreword included is by [[Martin Gardner]], and the 200+ illustrations are by David Povilaitis. Like other books by Rucker, ''The Fourth Dimension'' is dedicated to [[Edwin Abbott Abbott]], author of the novella ''[[Flatland]]''.
==Synopsis== ''The Fourth Dimension'' teaches readers about the concept of a fourth spatial dimension. Several analogies are made to ''Flatland''; in particular, Rucker compares how a square in Flatland would react to a cube in Spaceland to how a cube in Spaceland would react to a [[hypercube]] from the fourth dimension.
The book also includes multiple puzzles.
==Reception== ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called it "animated, often amusing", and a "rare treat", but noted that the book eventually leaves mathematical topics behind to focus instead on "mysticism of the all-is-one-one-is-all thinking of an [[Ouspensky]]."<ref name=Kirkus>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/rudy-rucker-2/the-fourth-dimension-toward-a-geometry-of-highe/ THE FOURTH DIMENSION: Toward a Geometry of Higher Reality], reviewed at ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]''; published October 8, 1984; retrieved June 27, 2018</ref> The ''[[Quarterly Review of Biology]]'' declared it to be "nice", and "at times (...) enchanting", comparing it to ''[[The Tao of Physics]]''.<ref name=QRoB>[Scott Ferson, "The Fourth Dimension: Toward a Geometry of Higher Reality. Rudy Rucker ," The Quarterly Review of Biology 61, no. 1 (Mar., 1986): 166.; https://doi.org/10.1086/414894</ref>
==See also== *''[[Hiding in the Mirror]]'', a similar book by [[Lawrence M. Krauss]].
